4 SYNOPSIS:
5 This bill would require agents of hostile
6 foreign principals who engage in political activity in
7 this state and foreign supported political
8 organizations that engage in political activity in this
9 state to register with the Secretary of State.
10 This bill would provide for the information that
11 must be included on registration forms and require
12 periodic registration updates.
13 This bill would authorize the Secretary of State
14 to impose civil penalties for violations of this act.
15 This bill would authorize persons upon whom a
16 civil penalty is imposed to appeal to the State Ethics
17 Commission.
18 This bill would authorize the State Ethics
19 Commission to reduce or set aside a civil penalty.
20 This bill would also define terms.
21
22
23 A BILL
24 TO BE ENTITLED
25 AN ACT
26
27 Relating to political activity; to require certain
28 agents of hostile foreign principals and foreign supported
Page 1

agents of hostile foreign principals and foreign supported
HB358 INTRODUCED
29 political organizations to register with the Secretary of
30 State; to establish registration requirements; to authorize
31 the Secretary of State to impose civil penalties; and to
32 authorize the State Ethics Commission to hear appeals.
33 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
34 Section 1. The Legislature finds all of the following:
35 (1) The voters, residents, and policymakers of Alabama
36 are entitled to transparency in the political and propaganda
37 activities of organizations that may be controlled by or under
38 the influence of foreign countries hostile to the interests of
39 the United States and the State of Alabama.
40 (2) In an increasingly globalized world, determining
41 whether an organization's political and propaganda activities
42 are funded by hostile foreign interests is often difficult.
43 (3) Legislation is needed to ensure the transparency
44 necessary to allow voters, residents, and policymakers to
45 evaluate whether political and propaganda activities are
46 funded by potentially hostile foreign actors.
47 Section 2. As used in this act, the following terms
48 have the following meanings:
49 (1) AGENT OF A HOSTILE FOREIGN PRINCIPAL. Any person
50 who acts as an agent, employee, representative, or servant, or
51 otherwise acts at the order, request, or under the direction
52 or control of a hostile foreign principal: (i) whose actions
53 are financed in whole or in part by a hostile foreign
54 principal; and (ii) who engages in political activity.
55 (2) COMMISSION. The State Ethics Commission.
56 (3) FOREIGN SUPPORTED POLITICAL ORGANIZATION. A
Page 2

(3) FOREIGN SUPPORTED POLITICAL ORGANIZATION. A
HB358 INTRODUCED
57 political organization or partnership, committee, association,
58 corporation, limited liability company, limited liability
59 partnership, trust, professional corporation, or any other
60 combination of persons that has, within the past five calendar
61 years, received money or other things of value from a hostile
62 foreign principal or an agent of a hostile foreign principal
63 and which engages in political activity. The term does not
64 include an industry, trade, or professional association that
65 exists to promote the interests of its members, or any
66 affiliated organization.
67 (4) HOSTILE FOREIGN COUNTRY. All of the following:
68 a. The Democratic People's Republic of Korea.
69 b. The Islamic Republic of Iran.
70 c. The People's Republic of China.
71 d. The Russian Federation.
72 (5) HOSTILE FOREIGN PRINCIPAL. Any of the following:
73 a. A government of a hostile foreign country, a
74 political party of a hostile foreign country, or any member of
75 a political party, body, or organization of a hostile foreign
76 country.
77 b. A nonresident alien of a hostile foreign country.
78 c. A partnership, committee, association, corporation,
79 limited liability company, limited liability partnership,
80 trust, professional corporation, or any other combination of
81 persons organized under the law of or having its principal
82 place of business in a hostile foreign country.
83 d. A domestic partnership, association, corporation,
84 organization, or other combination of persons that is at least
Page 3

organization, or other combination of persons that is at least
HB358 INTRODUCED
85 20 percent beneficially owned by a hostile foreign country, a
86 nonresident alien of a hostile foreign country, or an entity
87 organized under the laws of or having its principal place of
88 business in a hostile foreign country.
89 (6) POLITICAL ACTIVITY. Any activity that is performed
90 to influence any agency or public official of the state,
91 county, or municipality, or any state or local political
92 subdivision, or to influence the public within the state,
93 relating to the formulation, adoption, or change in the
94 policies or laws of the state or electing or opposing a
95 candidate for state or local public office.
96 Section 3. (a) No person shall act as an agent of a
97 hostile foreign principal unless he or she has filed with the
98 Secretary of State a true and complete registration statement
99 as required by this act. Every person who becomes an agent of
100 a hostile foreign principal, within 10 days of becoming an
101 agent, shall file with the Secretary of State a registration
102 statement, under oath, on a form prescribed by the Secretary
103 of State. The obligation of an agent of a hostile foreign
104 principal to file a registration statement shall continue from
105 day to day, and termination of that status shall not relieve
106 the agent from his or her obligation to file a registration
107 statement for the period during which he or she was an agent
108 of a hostile foreign principal. The registration statement
109 shall include all of the following, which shall be regarded as
110 material for the purposes of this section:
111 (1) The registrant's name, principal business address,
112 and all other business addresses in the United States or
Page 4

and all other business addresses in the United States or
